    - m_Type: 0
      Title:
        m_Untranslated: What is Exposure?
      Text:
        m_Untranslated: "In HDRP, mastering <b>Exposure</b> is important to achieve
          believable visuals.\r\n\r\nExposure is the amount of lighting affecting
          the sensor of a camera. Cameras, like your eyes, can automatically adapt
          to the amount of light in the environment. However, like in real life,
          it\u2019s important to control the exposure of your HDRP cameras to prevent
          over- or underexposure.\r\n\r\nThere are multiple exposure modes in HDRP.
          The most notable are:\r\n\r\n<b>\u2022 Fixed:</b> It allows you to manually
          set the Scene exposure precisely. As a result, the camera will not try
          to adapt to the lighting conditions when leaving or entering dark areas.
          It is used whenever the lighting conditions remain constant.\r\n\r\n<b>\u2022
          Automatic Histogram:</b> It simulates how a camera automatically adapts
          to dynamic lighting conditions within certain limits. This mode is utilized
          when dealing with a Scene having a wide variety of lighting intensities,
          such as indoor and outdoor areas."
